 {"id":"ids_ml_new-07b","title":"Implement realtime micro-batch IDS runtime","description":"What:\nImplement the v1 realtime runtime that accepts structured JSONL flow events from stdin and/or an input path, buffers them into small micro-batches, applies the contract/validator layer, scores valid records with the existing inferencer, and emits alert and quarantine outputs.\n\nWhy:\nFrom approach.md: this is the second HIGH-risk component and the core delivery of the feature. The runtime must prove that mixed valid/invalid input can be processed continuously without stalling, silently dropping records, or losing the final partial batch.\n\nContext from Planning:\n- Locked decisions D2, D3, and D4 apply exactly.\n- Runtime interface is structured JSONL for v1.\n- Output sinks are JSONL alert stream + JSONL quarantine stream + summary stats.\n- Do not introduce broker/web framework/packet sniffing dependencies.\n\nInstitutional Learnings:\n- No prior institutional learnings relevant to this feature.\n\nFile scope:\n- scripts/ids_realtime_pipeline.py\n- scripts/ids_feature_contract.py\n- scripts/ids_inference.py\n- tests/test_ids_realtime_pipeline.py\n\nVerification criteria:\n- Dry-run with mixed valid/invalid JSONL events shows valid records scored, invalid records quarantined, and schema-anomaly events emitted.\n- Flush behavior is deterministic for max_batch_size, flush_interval_seconds, and end-of-stream shutdown.\n- Valid records are not lost when malformed records appear in the same micro-batch.","notes":"Validated constraints from spikes ids_ml_new-ziz and ids_ml_new-yyi:\n- Support both CLI modes: if --input-path is provided, read JSONL from that file; otherwise read JSONL from stdin.\n- Preserve all non-model keys from the input event as passthrough metadata in alert/quarantine outputs, but never feed them into model scoring.\n- Runtime batches deterministically by explicit size/time triggers.\n- Record validation happens before scoring; invalid records are quarantined without blocking valid rows.\n- The runner must perform a final drain of buffered valid records on end-of-stream/shutdown.\n- Any alias handling used by the runtime is limited to explicit one-to-one normalization only.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-26T21:13:15.184778800Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-27T06:42:32.482338600Z","closed_at":"2026-03-27T06:42:32.481183500Z","close_reason":"Completed: added realtime JSONL micro-batch pipeline runtime","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ids_ml_new-07b","depends_on_id":"ids_ml_new-maj","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-26T21:13:39.939482600Z","created_by":"unknown","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"ids_ml_new-07b","depends_on_id":"ids_ml_new-u8s","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-26T21:13:40.058297Z","created_by":"unknown","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"ids_ml_new-07b","depends_on_id":"ids_ml_new-yyi","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-26T21:17:50.975006400Z","created_by":"unknown","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-0ab","title":"Resolve Review P2: Quarantine malformed normalized source keys","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nSource-key normalization strips whitespace and drops blank keys before quarantine logic runs. That means whitespace-variant keys can overwrite legitimate mapped fields and blank keys disappear entirely, so malformed upstream records may be silently altered instead of being quarantined with forensic visibility.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**File:** `scripts/ids_record_adapter.py`\n**Line(s):** 185-186\n\n**Why this is a problem:**\nThis loses evidence for records that did not map cleanly and can silently corrupt field selection before validation.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A — [Recommended] Detect malformed/duplicate normalized keys and quarantine them explicitly\n**Pros:** Preserves observability and prevents silent overwrites.\n**Cons:** Adds a stricter failure path for malformed upstream data.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n### Option B — Keep lossy normalization but document it\n**Pros:** No behavior change.\n**Cons:** Leaves silent corruption and evidence loss in place.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Blank source keys and normalized-key collisions are surfaced as explicit quarantine reasons.\n- [ ] Whitespace-variant keys cannot silently overwrite mapped values.\n- [ ] Regression tests cover blank keys and normalized-key collision cases.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-27T15:19:11.395364400Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-27T15:37:00.638785400Z","closed_at":"2026-03-27T15:37:00.636811300Z","close_reason":"Completed: quarantine blank and whitespace-colliding source keys before normalization can rewrite them","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-f4w::source-key-normalization-rerun","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["code-quality","review","review-p2"]}
+{"id":"ids_ml_new-0hbt","title":"Resolve Review P2: Add ML workflow regression and wrapper-smoke tests","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nSeveral migrated ML workflow modules now live under `ml_pipeline`, but the resulting automated coverage still centers on scaling, tuning helpers, and threshold analysis. Promotion, preprocessing, packaging, and training entrypoints were migrated without corresponding regression or wrapper-smoke coverage in the resulting test suite.\n\n## Evidence\n\nFiles:\n- `ml_pipeline/benchmark/stage_kaggle_benchmark.py`\n- `ml_pipeline/benchmark/stage_kaggle_promotion.py`\n- `ml_pipeline/data_prep/preprocess_iot_diad.py`\n- `ml_pipeline/packaging/package_final_model.py`\n- `ml_pipeline/training/train_iot_diad_binary.py`\n- `scripts/stage_kaggle_benchmark.py`\n- `scripts/preprocess_iot_diad.py`\n- `scripts/package_final_model.py`\n- `scripts/train_iot_diad_binary.py`\n- `tests/ml/test_stage_kaggle_scaling.py`\n- `tests/ml/test_tune_top_models.py`\n- `tests/ml/test_posttrain_threshold_analysis.py`\n\nWhy this is a problem:\n- The ML migration beads explicitly preserved wrapper surfaces and moved multiple workflow stages.\n- Missing regression coverage raises the risk of silent breakage outside the small subset currently exercised by tests.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A - Recommended: add targeted ML regression and wrapper-smoke tests for the migrated workflows\nPros: validates the critical moved entrypoints without requiring a full end-to-end training run.\nCons: adds more focused test scaffolding.\nEffort: Medium\n\n### Option B - narrow the supported surface and document the untested commands\nPros: less engineering effort now.\nCons: weakens the claimed phase-1 compatibility surface.\nEffort: Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Add regression or smoke coverage for migrated benchmark, promotion, preprocessing, packaging, and training entrypoints.\n- [ ] Cover the compatibility wrappers where phase-1 behavior is still promised.\n- [ ] Keep the added checks runnable in CI without requiring full training workloads.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-30T19:27:43.896013600Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-30T21:07:20.861937800Z","closed_at":"2026-03-30T21:07:20.860755300Z","close_reason":"Added ML workflow wrapper smoke coverage","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-br4g:ml-workflow-tests","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["migration-risk","review","review-p2","test-coverage"]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-1hs","title":"Spike: Is SQLite backup plus manifest restore safe enough if restore is forced offline and secret references are revalidated?","description":"Question to answer:\nIs the planned operator-console backup/restore contract technically sound if DB backup uses sqlite3 backup primitives online, but restore only runs offline with explicit service-stop and destination-validation preconditions, while secret material remains external and only secret references are restored?\n\nWhy this spike exists:\nApproach.md marks backup/restore + secret-reference validation as HIGH risk. The repo currently has no backup/restore seam, and same-host WAL behavior can make naive copy/restore claims unsafe.\n\nScope:\n- inspect current sqlite usage and operator-owned state surfaces\n- verify Python sqlite3 backup capabilities and restore implications for WAL-backed same-host use\n- determine minimum offline restore discipline and fail-closed secret-reference checks\n\nOutput:\n- write FINDINGS.md under .spikes/ids-operator-console-production-hardening/<spike-id>/\n- conclude YES or NO\n- if YES, list exact constraints for online backup, offline restore, manifest contents, and secret-reference validation\n- if NO, describe the blocker precisely\n\nSuccess bar for YES:\n- online backup path is real and supportable\n- restore preconditions are specific enough to avoid overstated safety claims\n- secret-reference semantics remain separate from secret material","status":"closed","priority":0,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-28T21:28:12.016238Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-28T21:31:41.647313200Z","closed_at":"2026-03-28T21:31:41.646549600Z","close_reason":"YES: sqlite backup API supports online snapshots, but restore must remain offline-only with manifest-based secret-reference validation and fail-closed preconditions.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["operator-console","production-hardening","spike","validating"]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-1mka","title":"Resolve Review P3: Tighten extractor follow-up type and invariant cleanup","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nThe review-follow-up refactor split extraction and serialization, but a few low-grade cleanup and type-invariant issues remain: a dead CSV formatter copy stayed in the extractor module, the serializer seam is typed with `Any`, and preflight still models `extractor_command_prefix` as optional despite normalizing it into a required tuple.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**Files:** `scripts/ids_offline_window_extractor.py`, `scripts/ids_offline_window_serializer.py`, `scripts/ids_live_sensor_preflight.py`\n\n**Why this is a problem:**\nThese do not break runtime today, but they weaken maintainability and make the new contract easier to drift accidentally.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A - [Recommended] Tighten the seam and remove dead helpers\n**Pros:** Makes the post-refactor boundary easier to reason about.\n**Cons:** Small touch across a few files.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Unused duplicate CSV formatting logic is removed or centralized.\n- [ ] The serializer seam uses a concrete type or protocol rather than `Any`.\n- [ ] Preflight models `extractor_command_prefix` as required all the way through config construction.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-30T13:46:27.679020700Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-30T13:48:55.398962100Z","closed_at":"2026-03-30T13:48:55.394729400Z","close_reason":"Completed: tightened seam typing and required-prefix invariants","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-vii9/review-seam-cleanup","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["code-quality","review","review-p3"]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-1rp","title":"Resolve Review P2: Cover malformed JSONL quarantine transport branches","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nMalformed JSONL transport branches are implemented but not covered by tests. The adapter is supposed to keep valid records flowing while quarantining invalid JSON or non-object payloads, yet those exact branches can regress without test pressure.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**File:** `scripts/ids_record_adapter.py`\n**Line(s):** 523-529, 585-606\n\nThe adapter has dedicated `invalid_json` and `invalid_record_type` quarantine handling, but the CLI tests only exercise valid JSONL and argparse rejection for unknown profiles.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A — [Recommended] Add mixed-stream malformed transport tests\n**Pros:** Verifies D9 behavior where valid and invalid records coexist in one stream.\n**Cons:** Slightly larger CLI test fixture surface.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n### Option B — Rely on manual dry-runs\n**Pros:** No code change.\n**Cons:** Leaves a regression-prone branch unguarded.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Add tests covering invalid JSON lines, non-object JSON payloads, and a valid record in the same stream.\n- [ ] Tests assert continued adaptation of valid records and correct quarantine fields for malformed entries.\n- [ ] `pytest -q tests/test_ids_record_adapter.py` passes.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-27T14:34:27.864215500Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-27T15:05:04.210777100Z","closed_at":"2026-03-27T15:05:04.208518300Z","close_reason":"Completed: covered malformed JSONL transport quarantine branches","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-f4w::malformed-jsonl-coverage","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["review","review-p2","test-coverage"]}
+{"id":"ids_ml_new-1w7v","title":"Rerun Review Cleanup Wave","description":"Final cleanup wave after the second post-fix review for repo-structure-rationalization. This epic captures the remaining validated P2/P3 findings: ids.core boundary tightening, docs lane cleanup, console security hardening, and wrapper smoke coverage expansion.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"epic","created_at":"2026-03-31T06:49:30.248440800Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-31T06:49:30.248440800Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"ids_ml_new-1w7v.1","title":"Tighten ids.core activation boundary and feature-column contract loader","description":"## Problem Statement\n\n`ids.core.model_bundle_activation` still owns activation-state behavior that should remain outside the core contract boundary, and `ids.core.feature_contract.load_feature_columns()` has already drifted from `ids.core.model_bundle.load_feature_columns()`. The review pass flagged this as a D9 boundary violation plus a growing DRY split inside the new core package.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Read-only/runtime-safe model-bundle helpers that truly belong in shared core are separated cleanly from operational lifecycle behavior.\n- [ ] `ids.core` no longer owns operational activation-state writes or status-building that should live in an explicitly operational surface.\n- [ ] Feature-column parsing/validation has one canonical implementation, with callers adapting exceptions only when they need domain-specific wrapping.\n- [ ] Focused core/runtime/ops tests cover the final boundary.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-31T06:49:39.175783Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-31T06:56:25.652982400Z","closed_at":"2026-03-31T06:56:25.649444500Z","close_reason":"Completed: separated activation writes/status into ops and centralized feature-column loader validation","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["architecture","code-quality","review","review-p2"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ids_ml_new-1w7v.1","depends_on_id":"ids_ml_new-1w7v","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-31T06:49:39.175783Z","created_by":"unknown","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
+{"id":"ids_ml_new-1w7v.2","title":"Clean up canonical docs lanes and mirrored test references","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nThe repo refactor introduced `docs/current` and `docs/archive`, but review still found ambiguous canonical claims and stale quick-start commands that teach the old flat test layout. This weakens D6/D7 and the intended navigation story for new maintainers.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Top-level legacy docs that still look canonical are converted into clear redirects/stubs or moved so `docs/current` is the unambiguous active lane.\n- [ ] Archive docs no longer point readers back to root-level canonical docs when a `docs/current/...` target exists.\n- [ ] Root README and current runbooks use the mirrored test layout or stable directory-based test commands that match the current tree.\n- [ ] Link/path checks and targeted doc grep verification pass.","status":"in_progress","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-31T06:49:51.001810600Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-31T06:54:11.035606800Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["architecture","docs","review","review-p2"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ids_ml_new-1w7v.2","depends_on_id":"ids_ml_new-1w7v","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-31T06:49:51.001810600Z","created_by":"unknown","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
+{"id":"ids_ml_new-1w7v.3","title":"Harden console restore integrity and redact unauthenticated health metadata","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nThe rerun review found two console security hardening gaps: backup restore trusts tamperable manifest/path data and never verifies the recorded digest before swap, and unauthenticated health/readiness endpoints expose sensitive filesystem and deployment metadata. Both issues live in the `ids.console` surface and should be fixed together before considering the branch review-clean.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Restore only accepts a backup payload rooted inside the selected backup directory and verifies the recorded digest before replacing the live database.\n- [ ] Failed restore validation does not leave the live database swapped to untrusted content.\n- [ ] Unauthenticated health/readiness responses are reduced to coarse safe status only; sensitive diagnostics move behind an authenticated/operator-only surface.\n- [ ] Security-focused tests cover both the restore integrity path and the redacted unauthenticated health contract.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-31T06:49:59.288880500Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-31T06:58:06.205627900Z","closed_at":"2026-03-31T06:58:06.204234100Z","close_reason":"Completed: hardened restore integrity and redacted unauthenticated health payloads","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["review","review-p2","security"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ids_ml_new-1w7v.3","depends_on_id":"ids_ml_new-1w7v","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-31T06:49:59.288880500Z","created_by":"unknown","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
+{"id":"ids_ml_new-1w7v.4","title":"Expand compatibility wrapper smoke coverage across ops and ML entrypoints","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nPhase-1 wrapper preservation is still under-tested. Review found that several deploy-facing `scripts.*` shims and several migrated ML wrappers are still not exercised by automated subprocess smoke coverage even though docs and runbooks continue to rely on those entrypoints.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Deploy-facing wrapper smoke coverage includes the documented `scripts.ids_model_bundle_manage`, `scripts.ids_operator_console_manage`, and `scripts.ids_operator_console_preflight` surfaces.\n- [ ] Where docs support direct file-path execution, smoke coverage proves the supported `python scripts/...py` path as well as representative `python -m scripts...` usage.\n- [ ] ML wrapper smoke coverage expands to include `scripts.posttrain_threshold_analysis`, `scripts.stage_kaggle_scaling`, `scripts.stage_kaggle_tuning`, and `scripts.tune_top_models`.\n- [ ] The added smoke coverage passes cleanly in the migrated mirrored test layout.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-31T06:50:08.070419500Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-31T06:57:50.227631900Z","closed_at":"2026-03-31T06:57:50.226808300Z","close_reason":"Completed: expanded wrapper smoke coverage for documented ops and ML entrypoints","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["review","review-p2","test-coverage"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ids_ml_new-1w7v.4","depends_on_id":"ids_ml_new-1w7v","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-31T06:50:08.070419500Z","created_by":"unknown","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-1z8","title":"Resolve Review P2: Enforce upstream-only profile inputs","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nThe shipped v1 profiles set `accept_canonical_feature_names=True`, which allows already-canonical 72-feature runtime records to pass through under either adapter profile. That widens the adapter boundary beyond the locked CICFlowMeter-like normalization scope and weakens the proof that the adapter is actually performing upstream-to-canonical mapping.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**File:** `scripts/ids_record_adapter.py`\n**Line(s):** 296-298, 787-803, 963-964\n\n**Why this is a problem:**\nIt violates the locked boundary that v1 profiles should prove explicit upstream normalization rather than quietly accepting already-canonical payloads.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A — [Recommended] Reject canonical passthrough by default in shipped profiles\n**Pros:** Restores the intended adapter boundary and reduces coupling to the runtime contract.\n**Cons:** Removes a convenience path for callers holding canonical payloads.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n### Option B — Keep passthrough but make it an explicit separate profile or flag\n**Pros:** Preserves the convenience path with a clearer contract.\n**Cons:** Expands the surface area and still needs documentation/tests.\n**Effort:** Medium\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] The default v1 profiles no longer accept already-canonical 72-feature payloads implicitly.\n- [ ] Any canonical passthrough mode is explicit and documented if retained.\n- [ ] Tests prove undeclared canonical feature payloads are rejected under the shipped profiles.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-27T15:19:11.116847500Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-27T15:34:30.303642900Z","closed_at":"2026-03-27T15:34:30.302603200Z","close_reason":"Completed: reject canonical-only payloads unless shipped profiles see upstream-specific source keys","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-f4w::canonical-boundary-rerun","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["architecture","code-quality","review","review-p2"]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-27c","title":"Resolve Review P2: Redact notification details in stack health output","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nThe new stack health layer explicitly opts into the operator console's sensitive notification payload shape and then prints that payload verbatim through the stack CLI. As a result, `status`, `smoke`, `recover`, and `post-restore-check` can expose the Telegram target plus raw notification `last_error` details in routine health output, even though the underlying health helper defaults to redacted mode.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**Files:** `scripts/ids_same_host_stack.py`, `scripts/ids_same_host_stack_manage.py`\n**Line(s):** 262-270 in `scripts/ids_same_host_stack.py`; 26-31 and 202-214 in `scripts/ids_same_host_stack_manage.py`\n\n```python\npayload = build_notification_component(load_stack_operator_config(config), include_sensitive=True)\n...\nprint(json.dumps(payload, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2, sort_keys=True))\n```\n\n**Why this is a problem:**\nThis widens the data-exposure surface of the canonical stack health commands and makes sensitive notification metadata easy to leak into operator consoles, automation logs, and monitoring systems.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A ? [Recommended] Keep stack health output on the redacted notification shape by default\n**Pros:** Aligns the stack surface with the existing least-exposure default and still preserves health semantics.\n**Cons:** Removes some troubleshooting detail from the default health output.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n### Option B ? Gate sensitive notification details behind an explicit diagnostic flag\n**Pros:** Preserves deep troubleshooting when an operator intentionally asks for it.\n**Cons:** Adds one more CLI/output mode to maintain.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Default stack `status`, `smoke`, `recover`, and `post-restore-check` outputs do not expose notification targets or raw `last_error` payloads.\n- [ ] Sensitive notification diagnostics require an explicit opt-in path instead of the default health contract.\n- [ ] Regression coverage proves the default stack payload keeps the notification section redacted.\n","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-29T14:10:44.110514900Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-29T14:27:32.353259300Z","closed_at":"2026-03-29T14:27:32.351641Z","close_reason":"Resolved in follow-up review-fix swarm: bootstrap verification, degraded payloads, redaction, and coverage expanded","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-x8y::security-notification-health-redaction","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["review","review-p2","security"]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-2e5","title":"Resolve Review P3: Cover missing bridge recovery branches","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nSeveral recoverable bridge error branches still have no dedicated regression tests: `extractor_runner_failed`, `missing_extractor_output`, `invalid_extractor_output`, and `unknown_adapter_profile`. Those are exactly the branches meant to preserve observability in the highest-risk extraction stage.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**File:** `scripts/ids_live_flow_bridge.py`, `tests/test_ids_live_flow_bridge.py`\n**Line(s):** missing-branch review evidence from the test-coverage reviewer\n\n**Why this is a problem:**\nFuture changes can silently break recovery/telemetry semantics in the extractor boundary without a targeted test failing.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A — [Recommended] Add focused branch tests for each recoverable bridge error\n**Pros:** Cheap, precise, and keeps the high-risk bridge boundary honest.\n**Cons:** Increases test count modestly.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n### Option B — Cover them indirectly through a broader integration test only\n**Pros:** Less unit-test surface.\n**Cons:** Makes diagnosis harder and can still miss payload-shape regressions.\n**Effort:** Medium\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Focused tests cover `extractor_runner_failed`, `missing_extractor_output`, `invalid_extractor_output`, and `unknown_adapter_profile`.\n- [ ] Assertions verify the `window_stage_error` payload shape, including `stage`, `reason`, and output-path fields.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-28T07:20:55.598949700Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-28T08:13:18.893365400Z","closed_at":"2026-03-28T08:13:18.890270600Z","close_reason":"Completed: bridge recovery branches now have focused regression tests for extractor and adapter error paths","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-vtc:bridge-branch-tests","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["review","review-p3","test-coverage"]}
