 {"id":"ids_ml_new-8ue","title":"Resolve Review P2: Assert absence of raw payload content in redaction tests","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nCurrent redaction tests assert only that the `source_record_redacted` flag is set. They do not verify that raw field values or malformed JSON text are actually absent from the emitted quarantine payload.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**Files:** `tests/test_ids_record_adapter.py`, `scripts/ids_record_adapter.py`\n**Line(s):** redaction tests check the flag but not absence of original keys, values, or raw JSON text.\n\n**Why this is a problem:**\nA regression could leak full payload content while still satisfying the current assertions.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A — [Recommended] Add absence-based redaction assertions\n**Pros:** Locks the security behavior instead of checking only a marker flag.\n**Cons:** Slightly more explicit fixture assertions.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n### Option B — Keep flag-only checks\n**Pros:** Smaller tests.\n**Cons:** Does not prove actual redaction.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Default redaction tests assert that representative source keys, values, and raw malformed JSON text are absent.\n- [ ] Opt-in raw capture tests remain as positive controls.\n- [ ] A regression that emits full raw content fails the suite.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-27T16:14:04.041292700Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-27T18:36:35.477131400Z","closed_at":"2026-03-27T18:36:35.474986200Z","close_reason":"Completed: redaction tests now assert raw payload content is absent by default","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-f4w::redaction-absence-tests-rerun-2","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["review","review-p2","test-coverage"]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-8wj","title":"Resolve Review P2: Preserve runtime batching boundary across windows","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nThe daemon calls `runtime_runner.finalize()` after each processed capture window, which collapses the downstream batching boundary into a per-window flush. That makes the planned `capture window + extractor runtime + micro-batch flush interval` latency model largely moot and increases runtime churn.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**File:** `scripts/ids_live_sensor.py`\n**Line(s):** window processing path around runtime finalize calls\n\n- Reviewer evidence from architecture highlighted the per-window finalize behavior around the runtime handoff in `scripts/ids_live_sensor.py`.\n\n**Why this is a problem:**\nThe planned architecture keeps the runtime stage window-agnostic and flush-controlled. Forcing finalize after each window weakens that separation and changes the operational latency/batching contract.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A — [Recommended] Decouple window processing from runtime finalization\n**Pros:** Preserves the planned batching boundary and makes flush controls meaningful.\n**Cons:** Requires clearer lifecycle ownership between daemon and runtime runner.\n**Effort:** Medium\n\n### Option B — Re-document the runtime as explicitly per-window\n**Pros:** Smaller code change.\n**Cons:** Rewrites the intended architecture and likely hurts throughput under higher traffic.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Window ingestion does not force a full runtime finalize after every closed window.\n- [ ] Runtime flush/finalize remains an independent control surface.\n- [ ] Tests cover successive windows without per-window forced finalize semantics.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-28T07:20:06.734456300Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-28T08:13:18.765910Z","closed_at":"2026-03-28T08:13:18.764918Z","close_reason":"Completed: daemon preserves runtime batching boundary and flush/finalize are now independent of each capture window","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-vtc","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["architecture","review","review-p2"]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-9973","title":"Add Regression Coverage And Docs For UI Redesign","description":"## Goal\nClose the redesign with regression coverage, compatibility verification, and doc updates.\n\n## What\n- Update route/rendering tests for the new IA, shell, and compatibility redirects.\n- Update reporting assertions if reports gain new summary/trend treatment.\n- Update operator documentation anywhere route/product naming changes matter.\n- Run the relevant operator-console pytest suites and ensure the final surface stays wired through the canonical server/app path.\n\n## Why\nThis feature has HIGH-risk route and shell changes; review will look for EXISTS / SUBSTANTIVE / WIRED and direct route references already exist in tests and docs.\n\n## File Scope\n- tests/test_ids_operator_console_web.py\n- tests/test_ids_operator_console_config.py\n- tests/test_ids_operator_console_reporting.py\n- docs/ids_operator_console_operations.md\n\n## Verification Criteria\n- Relevant operator-console pytest suites pass.\n- Legacy redirect behavior is covered.\n- Runtime/app-factory wiring and operator docs match the shipped UI vocabulary.\n\n## Context from Planning\nFrom approach.md: validating must inspect redirect strategy and route-wiring coherence.\n\n## Institutional Learnings\n- From history/learnings/20260328-operator-console-runtime-wiring.md: verify the wired runtime, not just the existence of templates/routes.\n- From history/learnings/critical-patterns.md: canonical contracts must execute what they claim.","acceptance_criteria":"Verification Commands\n- python -m pytest -q tests/test_ids_operator_console_web.py tests/test_ids_operator_console_config.py tests/test_ids_operator_console_reporting.py tests/test_ids_operator_console_auth.py\n- rg -n /overview|/operations|/dashboard|/anomalies tests/test_ids_operator_console_web.py tests/test_ids_operator_console_config.py docs/ids_operator_console_operations.md","notes":"Spike finding from ids_ml_new-u8xd must be embedded here: tests and docs must cover the new canonical routes plus explicit legacy redirects so EXISTS / SUBSTANTIVE / WIRED remains true at review time.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-29T18:29:09.706368400Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-29T19:05:12.285754400Z","closed_at":"2026-03-29T19:05:12.284472200Z","close_reason":"Completed: updated regression coverage and operator docs for the new console IA","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ids_ml_new-9973","depends_on_id":"ids_ml_new-6x7k","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-29T18:29:11.716044700Z","created_by":"unknown","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"ids_ml_new-9973","depends_on_id":"ids_ml_new-7y8m","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-29T18:29:11.318225100Z","created_by":"unknown","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"ids_ml_new-9973","depends_on_id":"ids_ml_new-mun0","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-29T18:29:10.890412400Z","created_by":"unknown","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"ids_ml_new-9973","depends_on_id":"ids_ml_new-mxm8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-29T18:29:10.516367800Z","created_by":"unknown","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
+{"id":"ids_ml_new-9ku3","title":"Resolve Review P2: Deduplicate shadowed live sensor health tests","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nOne relocated runtime-health test function is defined twice under the same Python name, so the later definition silently overwrites the earlier one. The suite therefore misses one of the intended malformed-summary scenarios even though the file appears comprehensive at a glance.\n\n## Evidence\n\nFiles:\n- `tests/runtime/test_ids_live_sensor_health.py`\n\nWhy this is a problem:\n- Python keeps only the last function definition with a given name.\n- This creates an invisible coverage hole in a refactor whose primary safety net is preserved behavior under the moved runtime package.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A - Recommended: rename/split the duplicated test cases and keep both scenarios\nPros: restores the missing coverage with minimal risk.\nCons: requires a small cleanup in one test module.\nEffort: Small\n\n### Option B - delete one case intentionally and document the dropped scenario\nPros: simpler if the scenario is redundant.\nCons: loses explicit edge-case coverage.\nEffort: Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Remove the duplicate test-name collision in `tests/runtime/test_ids_live_sensor_health.py`.\n- [ ] Preserve coverage for both malformed-summary scenarios intended by the current file.\n- [ ] The updated test module still passes under `pytest`.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-30T19:27:30.740621500Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-30T21:05:51.369096300Z","closed_at":"2026-03-30T21:05:51.366907Z","close_reason":"Completed: deduplicated shadowed malformed-summary tests in runtime health coverage","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-br4g:shadowed-health-tests","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["code-quality","review","review-p2","test-coverage"]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-9uk","title":"Resolve Review P3: Decouple core adapter imports from repo bootstrap","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nThe core adapter module mutates `sys.path` and builds filesystem-backed defaults at import time. This does not break the current repo use case, but it couples the reusable adapter API to the checkout layout and makes embedding or isolated imports harder than necessary.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**File:** `scripts/ids_record_adapter.py`\n**Line(s):** 11-18, 96-105\n\nThe module bootstraps repo imports and constructs default contract objects as import-time side effects.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A — [Recommended] Move bootstrap concerns to the CLI entrypoint and lazy factories\n**Pros:** Keeps the core API side-effect free and easier to embed.\n**Cons:** Some refactoring of module initialization.\n**Effort:** Medium\n\n### Option B — Keep the current import-time bootstrap\n**Pros:** Simple for this repo.\n**Cons:** Preserves tight coupling to the local checkout structure.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Importing the reusable adapter module does not mutate `sys.path` or require repo-layout side effects.\n- [ ] CLI behavior remains unchanged after bootstrap concerns move to explicit factories or the entrypoint.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-27T14:34:28.251557400Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-27T15:05:04.874328500Z","closed_at":"2026-03-27T15:05:04.873138100Z","close_reason":"Completed: moved repo bootstrap concerns out of module import side effects","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-f4w::repo-bootstrap-coupling","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["architecture","review","review-p3"]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-a6d1","title":"Resolve Review P2: Add failure-path coverage for restore inventory and post-restore gating","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nRestore verification is supposed to be a first-class stack contract under D13-D15, but the current tests only exercise one happy-path inventory case and two post-restore success cases. The implementation has substantial branch logic for selecting the effective backup directory, validating rebound secret references, classifying missing backup artifacts, and computing `post_restore_ready` from seven separate gates. Those failure paths are mostly untested, so regressions in the same-host restore contract can slip through while the suite still reports green.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**File:** `scripts/ids_same_host_stack.py`\n**Line(s):** 501-675, 756-849\n\n```python\ndef _require_operator_backup_dir(...):\n    ...\n    backup_dirs = sorted(..., reverse=True)\n    if not backup_dirs:\n        raise FileNotFoundError(...)\n\ndef _evaluate_secret_reference(...):\n    if source == \"file\":\n        ok = current_source is not None and Path(current_source).is_file()\n    ...\n    if ok and reject_placeholders:\n        ok = normalized not in PLACEHOLDER_SECRET_VALUES\n\npost_restore_ready = all([\n    inventory_payload[\"inventory_ready\"],\n    live_sensor_revalidation[\"ok\"],\n    recovery_payload[\"recovery_ready\"],\n    notification_ok,\n    final_status.get(\"ready\"),\n    final_smoke.get(\"ready\"),\n    bundle_visibility[\"ok\"],\n])\n```\n\n**File:** `tests/test_ids_same_host_stack_manage.py`\n**Line(s):** 654-696, 699-854\n\n```python\ndef test_build_stack_restore_inventory_restore_or_post_restore_checks_minimum_inventory(...)\ndef test_run_stack_post_restore_check_restore_or_post_restore_redrives_notifications(...)\ndef test_run_stack_post_restore_check_restore_or_post_restore_skips_disabled_notification(...)\n```\n\n**Why this is a problem:**\nThe feature's restore story is explicitly about failing closed on missing host state and proving recovery criteria after restore; without targeted failure-path tests, the highest-risk verification surface is only checked in the success direction.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A - [Recommended] Add restore failure-matrix tests\n**Pros:** Pins down the recovery contract where the approach identified the highest integration risk.\n**Cons:** Requires a few more fixture variants.\n**Effort:** Medium\n\n### Option B - Rely on component tests only\n**Pros:** Less new test code.\n**Cons:** Misses the stack-specific wiring and gating logic this feature introduced.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Add restore-inventory tests for missing manifest / backup DB, backup-root inputs that must select the newest `backup-*` directory, and secret-reference failures such as missing file rebound or placeholder inline values.\n- [ ] Add post-restore tests that prove `post_restore_ready` becomes false when any required gate fails, especially final `status`, final `smoke`, or bundle visibility re-establishment.\n- [ ] Add a notification-enabled failure test showing that a still-degraded `notify-status` / `notify-redrive` result blocks `post_restore_ready`.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-29T14:11:10.615271200Z","created_by":"RainyRiver","updated_at":"2026-03-29T14:27:32.375625Z","closed_at":"2026-03-29T14:27:32.374691800Z","close_reason":"Resolved in follow-up review-fix swarm: bootstrap verification, degraded payloads, redaction, and coverage expanded","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-x8y:test-coverage:restore-post-restore","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["review","review-p2","source-ids_ml_new-x8y","test-coverage"]}
