+{"id":"ids_ml_new-br4g.9","title":"Introduce the docs current/archive navigation spine","description":"Introduce the docs current/archive navigation spine.\n\nWhat:\n- Create docs/current and docs/archive as the canonical documentation split.\n- Update top-level README and docs index navigation so readers are directed to current material first and historical material second.\n- Leave domain-specific document rewrites and relocation to a separate bead.\n\nContext from Planning:\n- D7 requires canonical/current references to be visually distinct from historical or superseded material.\n- This bead creates the navigation frame first so later doc moves have a stable target.\n\nInstitutional Learnings:\n- Operators need one obvious canonical path for active contracts and runbooks.\n\nFile scope:\n- docs/current/**\n- docs/archive/**\n- README.md\n- top-level docs index files only\n\nAcceptance:\n- docs/current and docs/archive both exist.\n- README points readers to the current navigation spine and clearly distinguishes archived material.\n- No domain-specific content move is required to close this bead.\n\nVerify:\n- Test-Path docs/current\n- Test-Path docs/archive\n- Select-String -Path README.md -Pattern docs/current,docs/archive","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-30T15:12:08.258466800Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-30T18:36:50.837446600Z","closed_at":"2026-03-30T18:36:50.835625400Z","close_reason":"Completed: added docs current/archive navigation spine and README index wiring","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["docs","navigation","refactor"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ids_ml_new-br4g.9","depends_on_id":"ids_ml_new-br4g","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-30T15:12:08.258466800Z","created_by":"unknown","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"ids_ml_new-br4g.9","depends_on_id":"ids_ml_new-br4g.3","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-30T15:31:33.068544200Z","created_by":"QuietRiver","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
+{"id":"ids_ml_new-bs63","title":"Resolve Review P3: Replace wildcard wrapper exports with explicit compatibility shims","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nSeveral compatibility wrappers use wildcard re-exports (`from ... import *`) instead of explicit delegation. That makes the compatibility surface implicit, weakens static analysis, and makes the wrapper seams less intentional than the phase-1 plan called for.\n\n## Evidence\n\nFiles:\n- `scripts/ids_same_host_stack.py`\n- `scripts/ids_operator_console_manage.py`\n- `scripts/stage_kaggle_benchmark.py`\n\nWhy this is a problem:\n- Decision `D8` keeps wrappers as thin compatibility seams.\n- Wildcard exports obscure exactly what the wrapper promises to preserve.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A - Recommended: replace wildcard exports with explicit thin wrapper shims\nPros: clearer compatibility contract and easier static analysis.\nCons: slightly more boilerplate in wrappers.\nEffort: Small\n\n### Option B - keep wildcard exports and rely on comments\nPros: least code churn.\nCons: leaves the wrapper surface implicit.\nEffort: Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Replace wildcard re-exports in the identified compatibility wrappers with explicit delegation or explicit re-export lists.\n- [ ] Keep the wrapper surfaces behaviorally compatible.\n- [ ] Confirm the affected entrypoints still pass their smoke checks.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-30T19:27:53.873579500Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-30T21:13:35.832625500Z","closed_at":"2026-03-30T21:13:35.831640200Z","close_reason":"Completed: explicit compatibility shims for wrapper exports","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-br4g:wildcard-wrappers","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["code-quality","review","review-p3"]}
+{"id":"ids_ml_new-c00l","title":"Resolve Review P2: Decouple runtime bundle resolution from ops lifecycle module","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nRuntime-serving modules now import read-only active-bundle resolution from `ids.ops.model_bundle_lifecycle`. That creates a reverse dependency where the serving path depends on the operational lifecycle layer, even though the repo refactor aimed to reduce runtime/deploy cross-coupling.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**Files:** `ids/runtime/inference.py`, `ids/runtime/live_sensor.py`, `ids/runtime/live_sensor_health.py`\n\n```python\nfrom ids.ops.model_bundle_lifecycle import ActiveBundleResolutionError, resolve_active_model_bundle\n```\n\n**Why this is a problem:**\n`ids.ops` should own mutate/promote/manage lifecycle concerns. When `ids.runtime` depends on that layer for ordinary read-only bundle resolution, future ops changes can destabilize serving behavior and the intended domain boundaries become blurry.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A - Recommended: extract read-only activation resolution into a lower shared contract module\n**Pros:** Restores clean layering between serving and ops paths.\n**Cons:** Requires another small module split and import updates.\n**Effort:** Medium\n\n### Option B - Freeze the lifecycle module as a consciously shared read-only API surface\n**Pros:** Lower immediate churn.\n**Cons:** Keeps runtime coupled to an ops-named module and weakens the architecture map.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Runtime-serving modules no longer depend on an ops-named lifecycle module for read-only active-bundle resolution.\n- [ ] Promote/rollback/manage behavior remains in `ids.ops`.\n- [ ] The final import graph matches the intended runtime-vs-ops separation.\n\nSource epic: `ids_ml_new-br4g`","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-30T21:49:18.630490900Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-31T06:06:36.599117Z","closed_at":"2026-03-31T06:06:36.598287800Z","close_reason":"Completed: moved read-only activation helpers to ids.core and redirected runtime imports","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["architecture","migration-risk","review","review-p2"]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-c7y","title":"Resolve Review P3: Harden default streaming quarantine observability","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nIn streaming mode, quarantine events default to `stderr` and include the full raw source payload. That is acceptable for local debugging, but it is a weak default for shared logging environments because hostile or sensitive records can leak through central log pipelines.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**File:** `scripts/ids_record_adapter.py`\n**Line(s):** 339-341, 588-603, 660-666\n\nThe quarantine event retains full `source_record`, malformed-line branches place raw content into that field, and stdin mode defaults the quarantine sink to `stderr`.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A — [Recommended] Make full raw-payload emission opt-in or redact by default\n**Pros:** Safer default for shared stderr/log collectors.\n**Cons:** Slightly less convenient for debugging unless explicitly enabled.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n### Option B — Keep stderr full-payload output as-is and document the risk\n**Pros:** No behavioral change.\n**Cons:** Leaves sensitive or hostile payloads exposed in common deployment patterns.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Streaming-mode quarantine has a safer default than full raw-payload emission to `stderr`.\n- [ ] Any full-record emission mode is explicit and documented.\n- [ ] Tests or docs cover the new quarantine-output behavior.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-27T14:34:28.346133500Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-27T15:05:05.034942200Z","closed_at":"2026-03-27T15:05:05.033666100Z","close_reason":"Completed: made streaming quarantine payload redaction the safer default","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-f4w::streaming-quarantine-observability","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["review","review-p3","security"]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-cac","title":"Resolve Review P2: Cover mixed canonical and profile-specific payload rejection","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nThe current suite does not cover mixed canonical/profile-specific payloads. It only rejects a fully canonical record, leaving the mostly-canonical shortcut path unverified.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**Files:** `tests/test_ids_record_adapter.py`, `scripts/ids_record_adapter.py`\n**Line(s):** test coverage currently exercises canonical-only rejection but not mixed canonical/profile payloads.\n\n**Why this is a problem:**\nThe approach explicitly says the shipped profiles must not collapse into passthrough wrappers. Without mixed-payload tests, that guardrail is not locked.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A — [Recommended] Add mixed canonical/profile rejection cases for both shipped profiles\n**Pros:** Verifies the exact guardrail that distinguishes an adapter from a passthrough wrapper.\n**Cons:** A few more explicit tests.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n### Option B — Rely on implementation review only\n**Pros:** No additional test maintenance.\n**Cons:** Leaves a fragile boundary unprotected by regression coverage.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Tests cover canonical features plus profile-only metadata aliases.\n- [ ] Tests cover one aliased feature plus the remaining canonical features.\n- [ ] Both cases quarantine with the expected reason under shipped profiles.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-27T16:14:03.760666400Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-27T18:36:35.245656600Z","closed_at":"2026-03-27T18:36:35.243750800Z","close_reason":"Completed: mixed canonical and profile-specific payload rejection is now covered in tests","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-f4w::mixed-payload-coverage-rerun-2","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["review","review-p2","test-coverage"]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-cb1","title":"Resolve Review P2: Exhaustively verify shipped alias maps","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nThe review-fix pass still tests only a very small subset of the explicit alias tables for the primary and secondary profiles. Because the alias registry is the highest-risk semantic surface in this feature, a swapped or mistyped mapping elsewhere in the table could still pass current tests and silently corrupt model-facing features.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**File:** `tests/test_ids_record_adapter.py`\n**Line(s):** 982, 1086, 1141\n\n**Why this is a problem:**\nThe highest-risk mapping surface remains under-verified relative to the approach risk map.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A — [Recommended] Add exhaustive alias-table verification per shipped profile\n**Pros:** Protects the most correctness-sensitive contract in the adapter.\n**Cons:** Slightly larger regression surface.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n### Option B — Keep representative spot checks only\n**Pros:** Smaller tests.\n**Cons:** Leaves silent semantic swaps largely undetected.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Tests verify the full expected alias maps for both shipped profiles.\n- [ ] A broken alias entry outside the currently spot-checked fields would fail the suite.\n- [ ] Coverage remains easy to maintain when profile maps change.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-27T15:19:11.955561600Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-27T15:40:39.259779700Z","closed_at":"2026-03-27T15:40:39.258109300Z","close_reason":"Completed: verify the full shipped primary and secondary alias tables in tests","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-f4w::alias-map-coverage-rerun","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["review","review-p2","test-coverage"]}
