 {"id":"ids_ml_new-nd2s","title":"Resolve Review P2: Decouple extractor core from adapter serialization","description":"## Source Epic\\n- ids_ml_new-vii9\\n\\n## Problem\\nThe new offline extractor currently owns PCAP decoding, flow feature calculation, profile lookup, source-key alias mapping, metadata shaping, and CSV serialization in one module.\\n\\n## Evidence\\n- scripts/ids_offline_window_extractor.py imports adapter profiles directly and uses \feature_alias_map to emit adapter-shaped rows.\\n- CSV writing happens in the same module as semantic extraction.\\n\\n## Why It Matters\\nThis couples canonical extraction semantics to a specific adapter profile and output transport, which makes future adapter/profile changes bleed into the extractor core. That weakens the contract separation this feature was meant to clarify.\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- The extractor core exposes a canonical internal representation independent of profile alias maps.\\n- Profile-specific row shaping and CSV serialization move into a separate compatibility/serializer layer or equivalent seam.\\n- Existing bridge/adapter integration remains explicit and regression-tested after the split.\\n","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-30T12:07:09.081084900Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-30T13:14:00.142821600Z","closed_at":"2026-03-30T13:14:00.141422600Z","close_reason":"Completed: split canonical extractor flow extraction from profile-specific CSV serialization","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-vii9/review-extractor-adapter-boundary","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["architecture","review","review-p2"]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-nsb","title":"Resolve Review P3: Make file-mode raw quarantine capture opt-in","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nFile mode still forces raw `source_record` emission into the quarantine sidecar by default. That creates a quieter persistence path for attacker-controlled or sensitive payloads to land on disk even when operators did not explicitly opt in to raw quarantine capture.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**File:** `scripts/ids_record_adapter.py`\n**Line(s):** 360, 743\n\n**Why this is a problem:**\nThis is a defense-in-depth data-exposure concern on the quarantine path.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A — [Recommended] Make raw file-mode quarantine capture explicit opt-in\n**Pros:** Aligns file mode with a safer default and reduces accidental sensitive-data persistence.\n**Cons:** Slightly less convenient for local forensic workflows.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n### Option B — Keep the default and document the risk only\n**Pros:** No behavior change.\n**Cons:** Leaves the quieter persistence path in place.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] File-mode quarantine redacts or omits raw payloads by default.\n- [ ] Full raw-payload capture requires explicit operator opt-in.\n- [ ] Docs/tests cover the default and opt-in behaviors.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-27T15:19:12.558348900Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-27T15:43:27.684154300Z","closed_at":"2026-03-27T15:43:27.682420Z","close_reason":"Completed: make file-mode raw quarantine capture explicit opt-in and document the safer default","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-f4w::file-quarantine-raw-optin-rerun","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["review","review-p3","security"]}
 {"id":"ids_ml_new-o81","title":"Resolve Review P2: Unify shipped profile acceptance and contract source of truth","description":"## Problem Statement\n\nThe shipped profile acceptance surface is still partly derived from `DEFAULT_ADAPTER_FEATURE_COLUMNS` at runtime, while the adapter contract remains independently configurable. That leaves profile input acceptance and canonical validation anchored to different sources of truth and makes profile shape changes possible through artifact drift rather than explicit profile-definition changes.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**File:** `scripts/ids_record_adapter.py`\n**Line(s):** generated closed-profile map construction and adapter construction still allow profile acceptance to derive from `DEFAULT_ADAPTER_FEATURE_COLUMNS` apart from the contract instance.\n\n**Why this is a problem:**\nThis weakens the locked explicit-map boundary for v1 and creates a split-brain configuration risk between profile acceptance and contract validation.\n\n## Proposed Solutions\n\n### Option A — [Recommended] Bind profile acceptance to a single explicit contract source\n**Pros:** Eliminates silent drift and makes accepted source keys fully inspectable.\n**Cons:** Requires explicit profile-map materialization or eager compatibility validation.\n**Effort:** Medium\n\n### Option B — Keep runtime-derived acceptance and document the dependency\n**Pros:** Smaller change.\n**Cons:** Leaves profile behavior dependent on external artifact drift.\n**Effort:** Small\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Shipped profile acceptance is not widened or narrowed by `feature_columns.json` changes alone.\n- [ ] Adapter construction rejects registry/contract mismatches eagerly, or derives both from a single explicit source.\n- [ ] The accepted source-key surface for shipped profiles is directly inspectable.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-27T18:59:04.322309800Z","created_by":"unknown","updated_at":"2026-03-27T19:22:43.408915500Z","closed_at":"2026-03-27T19:22:43.407267500Z","close_reason":"Completed: bound shipped profile acceptance to explicit contract-compatible profile definitions","external_ref":"ids_ml_new-f4w::source-of-truth-rerun-3","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["architecture","code-quality","review","review-p2"]}
